WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.360
Shiny Assistant is an AI-powered tool for Shiny app development. In this video, we'll demonstrate

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:18.480
how to use it to build a Shiny for Python application and then run it within the Positron

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:26.799
IDE. Shiny Assistant is available at this URL and features a user-friendly chat for asking anything

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:33.200
about Shiny. Let's say you want to create a Shiny for Python-powered dashboard, but not sure where

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:39.599
to start. Let's ask Shiny Assistant to create a simple interactive dashboard with a few plots

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:47.119
and a table. Once we input our request, Shiny Assistant moves the prompt to the left sidebar

00:00:47.119 --> 00:00:52.480
and begins generating the application. Simultaneously, we see an instance of Shiny

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:58.240
live open, which will allow us to run and modify the application directly in our web browser.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:04.000
And here is the AI-generated Shiny for Python dashboard from Shiny Assistant,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.599
featuring two plots, a table, and interactive inputs. Let's take the code and copy it to an

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:18.239
app.py file within a new Python project in Positron. Before we can run the application,

00:01:18.239 --> 00:01:25.120
we need to install the necessary packages, including Shiny, NumPy, Pandas, and matplotlib.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:32.400
To install these packages, we'll open the terminal and run pip install followed by the package names.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.559
We also want to install the Shiny extension, which we can do by clicking the extensions button on the

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:44.800
left, searching for Shiny, and clicking install. Now that our environment is set, we can run the

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:54.000
application by clicking the play button. And here it is, our Shiny Assistant created dashboard,

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:03.199
now running within Positron.

